sec.p:
The inclusion of non-exponential distributions of the infectious period in epidemic models means that the chance of recovery depends on the time since infection, and hence the model needs to keep track of this information. Although this can be achieved in several ways, e.g. via an integro-differential equation formulation (Hethcote and Tudor 1980; Keeling and Grenfell 1997) or a partial differential equation formulation (Anderson and May 1992), a significant body of research has been focused on the method of stages (see, just to mention a few papers, Cunniffe et al. 2012; Lloyd 2001a, b; Sherborne et al. 2015), first introduced—to the best of our knowledge—by Cox and Miller (1965). It consists in assuming that the infectious period obeys a distribution of the type Erlang\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
